The `onlyEOAEx` modifier is intended to ensure that calls are made only from an externally-owned account (EOA) and not from a smart contract. However, with the introduction of EIP 3074, which introduces the `AUTH` and `AUTHCALL` instructions, this approach may no longer be effective.

To mitigate this vulnerability, we can modify the `onlyEOAEx` modifier to check if the `msg.sender` is an EOA or a smart contract using the `isContract` function. This function can be implemented using the `codehash` and `address` of the `msg.sender` to determine if it is a contract or not.

Here's an improved version of the `onlyEOAEx` modifier:
```
modifier onlyEOAEx() {
    if (!allowContractCalls &&!whitelistedContracts[msg.sender]) {
        if (isContract(msg.sender)) {
            // Check if the contract is whitelisted
            if (!whitelistedContracts[msg.sender]) {
                // If not, revert with an error message
                revert NOT_EOA(msg.sender);
            }
        }
    }
    _;
}

function isContract(address _address) internal view returns (bool) {
    uint256 codeLength;
    // Check if the contract has a code
    codeLength = _bytecodeLength(_address);
    // If the contract has no code, it's an EOA
    if (codeLength == 0) {
        return false;
    }
    // Otherwise, it's a contract
    return true;
}

function _bytecodeLength(address _address) internal view returns (uint256) {
    uint256 codeLength;
    // Get the bytecode length
    assembly {
        codeLength := extcodesize(_address)
    }
    return codeLength;
}
```
This improved `onlyEOAEx` modifier checks if the `msg.sender` is an EOA or a smart contract using the `isContract` function. If the `msg.sender` is a smart contract, it checks if the contract is whitelisted before allowing the call. This ensures that only authorized contracts can make calls to the contract, even in the presence of EIP 3074.

